@NODE "Mail_19" " Re: Blitz Basic PC "
From: David McMinn <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Date: 06-15-00 10:44:22
Subject: @{b}Re: Blitz Basic PC@{ub}

Hi Mark

> Regarding what's right/wrong with Blitz, it's really up to you guys to tell me!
> I have a million ideas concerning Blitz floating round in my head, and wouldn't
> really know where to begin explaining them all.

Please try :)

> So come on everyone, what IS right/wrong with AmiBlitz?!? Give me some crazy
> ideas to go on!

Don't worry, the stuff that was good is in here too, its not all just criticism.

1) Pointers when using the built in types. There is no way to access the value 
at that address unles you create a newtype such as

newtype.byte
	b.b
end newtype
*value_at_this_address.byte\b = something

which is a pain.

2) Pointers to arrays (of unknown or variable size). Again, you end up creating 
a newtype something like this:

newtype.bytearray
	b.b[0]
end newtype
*ptr_to_array.bytearray\b[3] = blah

Don't know how you'd get around this in the language though.

3) Editor. Fair enough TED was sort of separate from the compiler, but if 
possible could you make a set of CLI tools as the compiler etc? The IDE would 
obviously be set up to use these, but it would mean that you could use any IDE 
you wanted. Which would mean making the debugger a separate program, which 
maybe had its own interface? Oh, no limited line length in the editor either 
please.

4) Functions/statements were cool, but yeah, its better that you only have one 
type now and you use Return to return a value from it (yes, AmiBlitz used 
Function Return <value>).

5) You know that the libraries sucked (having fixed number of libs etc) but 
your plans for the PCBlitz sound better - being able to create them in any 
language, not just x86 asm. However, they were easy enough to use (just stick 
the file in the directory and run makedeflibs) - PCBlitz gonna be similar or do 
we not even need the makedeflibs step? On a related note, don't save the source 
files as tokenised! ASCII rules :) Although having syntax highlighting (doh, 
you've got that) and some sort of quickhelp thing (showed parameters etc in 
title bar of screen) in the editor was very useful.

6) The debugger was good, although with some of the extras that the REDDebugger 
provided it was even better. Very simple to use which was nice. Unlimited 
memory view windows would be nice too. And you MUST be able to see the source 
when you are stepping through in files that have been included, i.e.

XINCLUDE "somefuncs.bb2"
Stop
call_some_func_from_the_include{}
NPrint "blah"
; etc

when you called the function, you would only get shown this source file and the 
cursor would stay on the call_some... line. You need to be able to see whats 
happening.

7) related to above, a proper project system would be good, instead of having 
to (X)INCLUDE everything. which would also probably require the forward 
referencing of functions (doh, notice from the screenshots you've got forward 
referencing) - even if you need to do a C thing and create prototypes first.

8) Linked list system was good, although maybe it would be better that they 
were unlimited in size. Or maybe even selectable i.e. Dim List blah(20) would 
give a list only able to hold 20 items, whereas Dim List blah(-1) would be 
unlimited.

9) mouseable labels were cool.

10) garbage collection was good when you just wanted to hack up a quick'n'dirty 
program, being able to free the memory properly by yourself was good for doing 
proper progs.

11) optimiser would be nice :) (for the Basic code parts, obviosly libs should 
be fairly well optimised already)

12) gotta be able to check if somthing succeeded. prime example in AmiBlitz was 
the window command. erally easy to get it to fail, but you had no way of 
knowing if it did. If possible commands should return a value showing if they 
succeeded or not, and ideally if successful would return a pointer (for the 
power users)

13) shared variables (in functions) were good

14) making up variables on the fly were good, but sometimes led to difficult to 
track down errors if you made typo's. Maybe keep the make up variables on the 
fly, but you have to define them with deftype. Or you could generate a list of 
variables in the program which the programmer could have a look at, since you'd 
probably notice a variable that was obscure or typoed in that rather than in 
code.

15) Unlimited parameters to functions would be good

16) Macros were good, until you realise that its a pain in the arse using ! and 
then {}

17) Can't make it out from the screenshot, but I hope you are using ";" for 
comments - it looke like ":"!

18) The ability to get the address of a function would be good.

19) Quick types were good

20) use the x86 fpu! and if possible support other cpu enhancements, like MMX 
(if there's any use for it these days) and 3dNow. transparently of course, 
don't have to specifically compile versions for AMD, just have something like:
  if this_processor_has_3dnow
	do_3d_now_instructions
  else
	do_normal_x86_crap
  end if

21) It's universally acknowledge that the Blitz manual was poor (although I 
liked the user guide, thought that was OK and people bitched too much). But the 
docs need to be really good, and correct :) with some good examples. Explaining 
the system would be good, such as in AmiBlitz there was probably an example 
that went along the lines of:

; Open screen
Screen 0,blah,whatever....

; Open Window
Window 0,0,0,640,320,....

But no explanation of *why* to open a screen or window. Fair enough you could 
say that people should know this if they are using screens/windows, but perhaps 
they don't. A lot of beginners started with Blitz, and they may not have a 
clue, or understand jargon or whatever.

22) residents and view newtypes were good as a quick reference

23) on-line help was good too, although the one that came with AmiBlitz had a 
very cut-down data set and wasn't too much use.

24) Dim'ming arrays on the fly, using variables as the size was good: i.e. Dim 
blah.w(my_size)

25) Long live BlitzDude and the "OKEE DOKEE" requester :)

I think thats all I have to say about Blitz, most of my other hassles are 
specifically with Amiga specific things in it. If I think of any more I'll let 
you know though.


