>> Isn`t a gosub a bunch of gotos in disguise anyway?

> Not exactly.   It is a goto and save the return address (and probably
> push some registers onto the stack)

For asm

gosub -> JSR label
goto  -> JMP label

JSR puts the address of next instruction in stack, which it can be read
and then writen to PC (program counter) using RTS.

In basic goto is for alternate routing like "if ... else ... endif" and
"select ?  case ? case ? ... default  end select" stuff.
Gosub is for subroutine stuff like functions. the only difference
for normal functions is that gosubed subroutines doesn't use local
variables (=stack space for variables, which are freed before the function
returns).


Stack in gosub type subroutine:
 Free stack space, ReturnAdd, ... main program stuff


Stack in function type subroutine:
 Free stack space, Var5, Var4, Var3, Var2, Var1, param3,
  param2, param1, ReturnAdd, ... main program stuff

