accelerator removed speed-wise (I get bare A1200 speed on a 200MHz thing),
but still feels right, and you can run almost anything. Plus you get as much
memory as your PC allows, and with Picasso drivers installed (an absolute
MUST -- it sucks otherwise!), you get a more powerful graphics card than any
Amiga card, assuming your PC's card is less than a couple of years old.
Slowness and slight instability are the only problems, but I'll report how
it runs on a K6-II 550MHz in a few days ;) The thing that really makes it
for me is that it uses folders on your Windoze drive for its own drives and
directories -- you can copy stuff between the "Amiga" and PC just by
dragging and dropping in Windoze, which means you can use Amiga programs to
generate graphics (or whatever) for use on the PC side if you're really
attached to a particular program. I use a drawer buried in my UAE setup to
store all graphics I make in -- with a shortcut on the desktop, you can just
open it up right there, save to it easily, etc. Hit Update in the open Amiga
drawer's Window menu and there they are :) If you have it set to use the
full screen, there's NO WAY to tell that it's UAE (apart from the speed ;)

