@NODE "Mail_231" " Re: Waiting on multiple ports "
From: David McMinn <dave@satanicdreams.com>
Date: 06-10-00 13:28:46
Subject: @{b}Re: Waiting on multiple ports@{ub}

Nick Lamburn's head burst.
All we could scrape off the wall was Waiting on multiple ports.

> Now I could 'OR' the userports all together, but the problem is that any

What do you mean could, thats what you /have/ to do! Just check the window
pointers, OR'ing in 0 doesn't do anything, i.e.

For i.w=1 to 5
	If *win(i) Then waitmask.l = waitmask | *win(i)\UserPort\mp_SigBit
Next

> number of windows can be open (1-5) at the time, and I'm not sure it would
> work.  It could be possible to OR all five, even when there is no window
> open there, but how do I know which Window was actually affected?
 
There is a field in the IntuiMessage called IDCMPWindow which is a pointer to
the window which had the event.

If you are going to have lots of multiple windows, it is far better to use a
shared IDCMP message port. There's info in the RKRMs (or maybe it's the
Autodocs) on how to do this. But its fairly simple:

1) Create a message port
2) When opening windows, pass 0 for the IDCMP flags and then use ModifyIDCMP to set
up the IDCMP flags. Put the pointer to your mesasge port into the Window
UserPort.
3) When processing events, IDCMPWindow is still used, but now you only have to
wait for 1 window, giving you the full 15 other user signals
4) when closing the window, use ModifyIDCMP to set  the IDCMP for the wqindow to
0, set the UserPort to 0 and then go through the messages waiting at the message
port, Remove_'ing then Reply_'ing all those messages which should have gone to
the window you are closing. The C code for this is in the
intuition.library/CloseWindow autodoc.

Bye
